  "prompt": "What is 6/6 myopia vision?",
  "response": "Myopia, also known as nearsightedness, is a common refractive error in which close objects can be seen clearly, but distant objects appear blurry. The term \"6/6 vision\" refers to a common standard for visual acuity used in some countries, equivalent to 20/20 vision in the United States. Specifically, it means that a person can see clearly at 6 meters what a person with normal vision can see at that same distance.\n\nWhen someone refers to \"6/6 myopia vision,\" it typically indicates that the individual has myopia but is able to see at a visual acuity equivalent to normal vision (6/6 in this case). This means that, despite having myopia, their vision may be corrected with glasses or contact lenses to achieve that standard.\n\nIn summary, \"6/6 myopia vision\" implies that the person has myopia (nearsightedness) but their vision is corrected well enough, typically through corrective lenses, that they can see at the same clarity as someone with normal vision at 6 meters.",
